{% if api_style == "spring-mvc" %}
## HTTP Model: Spring MVC

Use the blocking servlet stack when:

- the application is request/response heavy rather than stream-heavy
- most dependencies are blocking anyway (JPA, traditional drivers, external SDKs)
- operational simplicity matters more than extreme connection scaling

### Conventions

- Controllers return `ResponseEntity<?>` only when status or headers vary; otherwise return typed DTOs directly
- Global error handling lives in `@RestControllerAdvice`
- Synchronous service methods keep flow easy to debug and easier for most teams to reason about

{% else %}
## HTTP Model: WebFlux

Use WebFlux when non-blocking I/O is a deliberate design choice end-to-end.

### Conventions

- Controllers return `Mono<T>` / `Flux<T>`
- Do not mix reactive handlers with blocking repositories on the hot path
- Keep reactive chains shallow; move mapping logic into named methods or dedicated components
- Timeouts, retries, and circuit-breaking rules must be explicit for all outbound calls

{% endif %}

