## Security

{% if use_auth and auth_method == "jwt" %}
Authentication uses JWT bearer tokens. Token parsing belongs in security filters or resource-server configuration, while authorization decisions stay close to the use case.
{% elif use_auth and auth_method == "oauth2" %}
Authentication uses OAuth2 / OIDC resource-server flows. Keep issuer, audience, and scope mapping explicit in configuration and tests.
{% elif use_auth and auth_method == "api-key" %}
Authentication uses API keys. Treat this as an operational convenience pattern, not a substitute for fine-grained user identity when product requirements need it.
{% else %}
No auth scaffold is assumed. Internal trust assumptions still need documentation at system boundaries.
{% endif %}

Security rules:

- Authorization happens in services or dedicated policy components, not sprinkled across controllers
- Every externally exposed mutation path must have an authorization story
- Secrets come from environment-specific configuration, never committed defaults
- Audit-relevant actions should emit structured logs with actor, target, and outcome

---

## Testing Strategy

{% if test_strategy == "junit-only" %}
Focus on unit tests and Spring slice tests. This is the fastest feedback loop, but it requires discipline to avoid over-trusting mocks.
{% elif test_strategy == "junit-and-testcontainers" %}
Use unit tests for pure logic and Testcontainers-backed integration tests for persistence and infrastructure edges. This is the recommended default because it catches wiring drift early.
{% else %}
Use the full pyramid: unit, slice, integration, and a thin end-to-end layer for the critical business journeys.
{% endif %}

Minimum expectations:

- services have deterministic unit tests
- controllers have request/validation/error-path coverage
- repository behavior is verified against a real database where it matters
- authentication and authorization have explicit happy-path and denial-path tests
